IML 67577 — Challenge 2: Robust Image Classification (20 ImageNet-subset classes).
Everything is trained from random init; no pretrained weights, no external data, no
network access at train/load/eval. Every technique below maps to the course; the two
syllabus-edge choices (BatchNorm, residual connections) are flagged with their defense.

MODEL (model.py — class ModelArchitecture, ~11.2M params)
A small ResNet-18-shaped CNN: a stem (7x7 stride-2 conv → BatchNorm → ReLU → 3x3 stride-2
maxpool, 224→56) followed by 4 residual stages with channel widths 64→128→256→512, then
AdaptiveAvgPool2d(1) → Dropout(0.4) → Linear(512,20) logits. The first block of stages 2-4
strides 2 (28→14→7) and doubles channels; its identity branch is matched by a 1x1 conv+BN.
Spatial path: 224 → 112 (stem conv) → 56 (maxpool) → 56 → 28 → 14 → 7 → GAP → 20 logits.
The adaptive pool makes the net size-agnostic, so it accepts the grader's 224x224 input.

Why this shape, in course terms:
- Conv + pooling (Max/Avg/Stride), ReLU, softmax (argmax in predict.py), Global Average
  Pool instead of large fully-connected layers (no FC params before the final 512→20
  linear, which fights overfitting) — all from the CNN/regularization lectures.
- Residual / skip connections y = f(x)+x (He 2016, taught in the Transformers unit as the
  vanishing-gradient fix, same role as the LSTM forget gate). Examiner note: it is the
  SAME mechanism, here applied to convs rather than attention blocks; the skip gives
  gradients a direct path backward so the added depth is actually usable.
- BatchNorm after each conv. Only LayerNorm was taught (after each Transformer attention
  block, LayerNorm(x)=x−mean rescaled); BatchNorm is the same idea — a normalization
  layer — adapted to conv feature maps (it normalizes each channel across the batch and
  spatial positions). Its learned scale/shift and running mean/var ride in the state_dict
  as buffers, and predict.py calls .eval(), so inference uses the frozen running statistics
  and is batch-size-independent. (GroupNorm was our lower-risk fallback.) Normalization is
  the main reason a deep-from-scratch net trains cleanly and beats the old plain VGG.
- Regularization for the bias-variance tradeoff (11.2M params on only ~16k images is the
  main overfitting risk): head Dropout 0.4 (within the ~50% range taught), L2/Ridge weight
  decay (in training), Global Average Pool, and heavy data augmentation. Dropout holds no
  parameters, so it is the one knob we can retune from error analysis without regenerating
  weights or breaking weight loading.
- Weights init with Kaiming/He (fan-out, ReLU); the course taught generic "random init",
  this is a sensible random-init scheme tuned for ReLU fan-out.

TRAINING (train.py)
SGD with momentum 0.9 (NOT Adam — Adam is out of syllabus; plain SGD generalizes better
from scratch, which matters for the OOD half; momentum 0.9 is a standard smoothed-update
extension, stepping along a decaying average of past gradients, recovering vanilla SGD at
momentum 0). Loss = cross-entropy with label smoothing 0.1 (course-taught cross-entropy +
a soft-target extension; targets 0.9 true / 0.1 spread over the other 19, which curbs
over-confidence and discourages hard commitment to background/colour shortcuts — helps OOD;
drops to standard hard labels at 0.0). LR = 0.05 with a StepLR step-decay (×0.1 about twice
over the run, "learn fast early, fine-tune late"); the higher 0.05 is safe precisely because
BatchNorm conditions the loss surface, and grad_clip=1.0 is the safety net. Weight decay
5e-4 (= L2/Ridge). Early stopping on validation accuracy (patience, with best-weights
checkpointing) is the textbook overfitting guard. We rely on the saved weights.joblib rather
than rerun-determinism because MPS/CUDA kernels are not bit-deterministic. We follow the
ML-in-practice methodology: a stratified, seeded split; a naive logistic-regression floor
the CNN must beat; manual error analysis on Dev; and the local Test block touched once.

MANIPULATIONS / ROBUSTNESS (the 50% OOD half)
The graded test is 50% clean + 50% held-out manipulations, so we force invariance with
in-syllabus data augmentation (taught on MNIST: elastic distortions / training-set
expansion). We pre-bake OFFLINE augmented "twins" of the training images to disk (seeded
per file, so all teammates train on identical, inspectable data; twins inherit their
original's split partition, so no leakage). Originals pass through unchanged. Filters are
weighted and sampled without replacement so the CONFIRMED test axes dominate:
- Colour jitter (saturation/brightness/contrast 0.5–1.5, weight 4) — lighting + colour axis.
- Mean-fill rotation (45/90/180/270, corners filled with the image's own mean colour, not
  black; weight 4) — geometric axis and our nearest in-bounds proxy for a background change.
- Grayscale and colour inversion — break reliance on absolute colour (inversion weight 1,
  kept rare because it is label-risky: a yellow lemon becomes blue).
- Salt-pepper noise and blur (weight 2) — sensor noise / compression artifacts.
Rotation and colour jitter are weighted heaviest because the provided augmentations folder
confirms they are the real test manipulations. We deliberately do NOT attempt background
swap: it requires foreground/background segmentation plus external background assets, which
violates the train-from-scratch / no-external-data-or-models constraint and is not taught;
mean-fill rotation is the closest in-bounds "the surroundings changed" proxy. We track a
single SCORE = 0.5·clean + 0.5·mean(OOD-set accuracy) mirroring the grader's weighting, and
optimize that — not clean accuracy alone — confirming each augmentation trade is net-positive.
